        <!--Begin Direct vs. FFEL-->
        <h3 class="btn-About">Direct vs. FFEL</h3>
        <div id="aboutDirectFFELPFaq">
            <h4 class="questions">What is the difference between Direct and FFEL Loans?</h4>
            <p class="answers-aboutDirect1 answers" id="DirectAnswer1">
                The main difference between Direct Loans and Family Federal Education Loan Program
                (FFELP) loans is the source of funding. The funds for FFELP loans came from financial
                institutions, whereas the funds for Direct Loans come directly from the U.S. Department
                of Education, from the U.S. Treasury.
            </p>
            <h4 class="questions">What repayment plans are available through each loan program?</h4>
            <p class="answers-aboutDirect2 answers" id="DirectAnswer2">
                Most repayment plans are the same, including standard repayment, extended repayment
                and graduated repayment; other repayment plans are specific to the loan program.
                Income-Contingent Repayment (ICR) is available only to Direct Loan borrowers and
                Income-Sensitive Repayment (ISR) is available only to FFELP borrowers. Income-Based
                Repayment (IBR) is a new program available to both loan programs. Pay As You Earn is a repayment program based on your income.For more information about repayment plans visit our <a href="@Url.Content("~/Payments/RepaymentPlans")">Repayment Plans</a> page.
            </p>
        </div>
        <!--End Direct Vs FFELP-->
